^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|Howard, not all my opponents always are accommodating. For example what should our partnership do if I open 2H, for example, and the auction goes 2H-P-2N-3of a Suit-?|
PG| ***** 56 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Glad to explain. Many people have devised somewhat complicated systems over doubles (if interested, read about DOPI, DOPE, and DEPO), but I use a simple approach, based on stolen bid doubles. Generally speaking, pass means I would have responded with a bid below whatever the overcall was, double means the opponents "stole" my bid, and otherwise I bid what I would have without interference. There are some slight variations, depending on what is overcalled.|
PG| ***** 57 ***** |


AT|

1) Over 3D, pass means I would have responded 3C, double means I would have responded 3D, and 3H and 3S mean the same as if there were no interference.|
PG| ***** 58 ***** |


AT|

2) Over 3H, pass means I would have responded 3C or 3D, double means I would have responded 3H, and 3S means the same as if there were no interference.|
PG| ***** 59 ***** |


AT|

3) Over 3S, pass means I would have responded 3C or 3D, and double means I would have responded 3H or 3S.|
PG| ***** 60 ***** |


AT|

4) Over 3C, you can just use the normal approach -- double means I would have responded 3C and 3D/3H/3S mean the same as if there were no interference. Since pass is also available, I play a small wrinkle, but it is certainly optional, and you need not play it. If I pass, that says I would have bid 3C, but I have some defense and am willing to play 3C. If I double, that says I opened the usual hondo trash with little defense.|
PG| ***** 61 ***** |


cp||AT|

^B@2^*BMovie Maker: ^*N|cp||at|BTW, I assume that the 2NT bid is forcing.|
PG| ***** 62 ***** |


cp|8|AT|

^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Correct. It is forcing for one round.|
PG| ***** 63 ***** |


